   "source": [
    "# Wavelet Analysis: Detecting African Easterly Waves\n",
    "\n",
    "In previous sections, we looked at Fourier analysis, which breaks down a time series into its constituent frequencies. However, Fourier transforms assume that the signal is *stationary*\u2014meaning the frequency content does not change over time.\n",
    "\n",
    "Climate data is rarely stationary. For example, African Easterly Waves (AEWs)\u2014synoptic-scale disturbances that propagate westward across Africa\u2014are highly active during the West African Monsoon season (July-September) but absent in the winter. A standard Fourier transform would tell us that a 3-5 day periodicity exists in the annual data, but it wouldn't tell us *when* it occurred.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Wavelet analysis** solves this by using localized wave-like functions (wavelets). By stretching and shifting these wavelets across our time series, we can build a 2D picture of frequency (or scale) *and* time.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Morlet Wavelet\n",
    "The most common wavelet used in climate analysis is the Morlet wavelet. It is essentially a complex sine wave localized by a Gaussian envelope:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\\\psi_0(\\\\eta) = \\\\pi^{-1/4} e^{i \\\\omega_0 \\\\eta} e^{-\\\\eta^2/2}$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where:\n",
    "* $\\\\eta$ is a non-dimensional time parameter.\n",
    "* $\\\\omega_0$ is the non-dimensional frequency (usually set to 6, which makes the wavelet scale roughly equivalent to the Fourier period).\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's build a Continuous Wavelet Transform (CWT) entirely from scratch using only `numpy`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "# 1. Define the Morlet Wavelet function\n",
    "def morlet_wavelet(t, w0=6.0):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Generates a Morlet wavelet.\"\"\"\n",
    "    # The pi**(-0.25) factor ensures unit energy\n",
    "    return np.pi**(-0.25) * np.exp(1j * w0 * t) * np.exp(-0.5 * t**2)\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Build the CWT from scratch\n",
    "def cwt_scratch(data, dt, scales, w0=6.0):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Computes the Continuous Wavelet Transform from scratch.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "    data: 1D array of our time series (e.g., wind anomalies)\n",
    "    dt: time step (e.g., 1 day)\n",
    "    scales: Array of scales to compute\n",
    "    w0: Central frequency of the Morlet wavelet\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    cwt_matrix: 2D complex array of wavelet coefficients\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    n = len(data)\n",
    "    cwt_matrix = np.zeros((len(scales), n), dtype=complex)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Loop over each scale\n",
    "    for i, s in enumerate(scales):\n",
    "        # Create a time vector for the wavelet that covers the Gaussian envelope\n",
    "        # We go up to 8 standard deviations to ensure it decays to near zero\n",
    "        t_wavelet = np.arange(-8*s, 8*s, dt)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Generate the scaled wavelet\n",
    "        # The 1/sqrt(s) term normalizes the wavelet to preserve energy across scales\n",
    "        wavelet = morlet_wavelet(t_wavelet / s, w0) * (1 / np.sqrt(s))\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # The transform is the convolution of the data with the complex conjugate of the wavelet\n",
    "        # mode='same' ensures the output length matches our data array length\n",
    "        cwt_matrix[i, :] = np.convolve(data, np.conj(wavelet), mode='same') * dt\n",
    "        \n",
    "    return cwt_matrix"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Application: Detecting African Easterly Waves (AEWs)\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we will apply our bespoke code to a real-world climate problem. AEWs are characterized by fluctuations in the meridional (north-south) wind component (V-wind) at the 700 hPa pressure level. They typically have a periodicity of **3 to 5 days**.\n",
    "\n",
    "To demonstrate this, we will generate a synthetic time series representing one year of daily V-wind anomalies over West Africa. We will inject a strong 4-day wave packet right in the middle of the summer monsoon season (Days 180 to 250), surrounded by random atmospheric noise."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create a synthetic 1-year daily time series (365 days)\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "days = np.arange(0, 365)\n",
    "dt = 1.0 # 1 day resolution\n",
    "\n",
    "# Base background noise (weather variability)\n",
    "v_wind = np.random.normal(0, 1.5, size=len(days))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Inject an African Easterly Wave (4-day period) during the summer (Days 180-250)\n",
    "aew_period = 4.0 \n",
    "aew_frequency = 2 * np.pi / aew_period\n",
    "summer_envelope = np.exp(-0.5 * ((days - 215) / 25)**2) # Gaussian envelope peaking at day 215\n",
    "v_wind += 4.0 * np.sin(aew_frequency * days) * summer_envelope\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the raw data\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "plt.plot(days, v_wind, color='teal')\n",
    "plt.title('Synthetic 700 hPa Meridional Wind Anomaly (West Africa)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Day of Year')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('V-wind Anomaly (m/s)')\n",
    "plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Looking at the raw time series, we can see the increased variance during the summer, but it's messy. Let's run our `cwt_scratch` function to isolate the temporal and frequency signature of the AEW. \n",
    "\n",
    "For a Morlet wavelet with $\\\\omega_0 = 6$, the relationship between wavelet scale $s$ and Fourier period $T$ is roughly $T \\\\approx 1.03 s$. For simplicity, we can assume scale and period are nearly 1:1."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Define scales to investigate (e.g., periods from 1 to 20 days)\n",
    "scales = np.arange(1, 21, 0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Run our bespoke CWT\n",
    "cwt_bespoke = cwt_scratch(v_wind, dt, scales)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate Wavelet Power (squared absolute value of coefficients)\n",
    "power_bespoke = np.abs(cwt_bespoke)**2\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the Scalogram\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))\n",
    "# We use extent to align axes: [xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax]\n",
    "plt.imshow(power_bespoke, extent=[0, 365, scales[-1], scales[0]], \n",
    "           aspect='auto', cmap='magma', interpolation='bilinear')\n",
    "plt.gca().invert_yaxis() # Put short periods (high freq) at the bottom\n",
    "plt.colorbar(label='Wavelet Power')\n",
    "plt.title('Wavelet Power Spectrum (Bespoke Code)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Day of Year')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Period (Days)')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Highlight the AEW band\n",
    "plt.axhline(y=3, color='white', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "plt.axhline(y=5, color='white', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "plt.text(20, 4, 'AEW Band (3-5 days)', color='white', verticalalignment='center')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Using a Standard Package (`PyWavelets`)\n",
    "\n",
    "Writing the CWT from scratch teaches us exactly what the algorithm is doing: sliding a scaled wave across our data and measuring the resonance. However, in standard research environments, we use optimized libraries. These libraries handle edge effects (the \"Cone of Influence\"), significance testing against red noise backgrounds, and execute much faster using FFTs.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's use the standard `PyWavelets` (`pywt`) library to perform the same analysis and compare the results to ensure our bespoke code is mathematically sound.\n",
    "\n",
    "*(Note: You may need to run `!pip install PyWavelets` if you do not have it installed).*"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pywt\n",
    "\n",
    "# PyWavelets uses continuous wavelets. 'cmor1.5-1.0' defines a complex Morlet \n",
    "# The parameters define the bandwidth and center frequency (equivalent to w0=2*pi roughly)\n",
    "# To match our w0=6, we use 'cmor1.0-0.955' (where 0.955 approx = 6 / (2*pi))\n",
    "wavelet_name = 'cmor1.0-0.955'\n",
    "\n",
    "# PyWavelets requires us to define scales differently depending on the wavelet to map to exact frequencies\n",
    "# For an exact comparison, we will feed it our predefined scales\n",
    "cwt_pkg, freqs_pkg = pywt.cwt(v_wind, scales, wavelet_name, sampling_period=dt)\n",
    "\n",
    "power_pkg = np.abs(cwt_pkg)**2\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the Package Scalogram\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))\n",
    "plt.imshow(power_pkg, extent=[0, 365, scales[-1], scales[0]], \n",
    "           aspect='auto', cmap='magma', interpolation='bilinear')\n",
    "plt.gca().invert_yaxis()\n",
    "plt.colorbar(label='Wavelet Power')\n",
    "plt.title('Wavelet Power Spectrum (PyWavelets Package)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Day of Year')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Period (Days)')\n",
    "plt.axhline(y=3, color='white', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "plt.axhline(y=5, color='white', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Verify the difference between our scratch code and the package\n",
    "# (Allowing for tiny differences due to edge handling and normalization conventions)\n",
    "difference = np.mean(np.abs(power_bespoke - power_pkg))\n",
    "print(f\"Mean Absolute Difference between bespoke and package power: {difference:.4f}\")"
   ]
  }
